  "prompt": "Biochemistry: What are the most common types of protein damage caused by reactive nitrogen species?",
  "response": "Reactive nitrogen species (RNS) can cause several types of protein damage. Here are the most common types:\n\n1. Protein Nitration\n- Involves addition of nitro (-NO2) groups to tyrosine residues\n- Forms 3-nitrotyrosine\n- Alters protein structure and function\n- Can impair enzymatic activity and protein interactions\n\n2. Protein Nitrosylation\n- Adds nitric oxide (NO) to cysteine thiol groups\n- Forms S-nitrosothiols\n- Can modify protein conformation and activity\n- Affects signaling and regulatory mechanisms\n\n3. Carbonylation\n- Introduces carbonyl groups into protein side chains\n- Results from oxidative modifications\n- Leads to protein structural changes\n- Often associated with oxidative stress\n\n4. Protein Fragmentation\n- Direct protein backbone cleavage\n- Caused by severe oxidative damage\n- Reduces protein functionality\n- Can lead to protein degradation\n\n5. Cross-linking\n- Creates abnormal protein-protein interactions\n- Can form covalent bonds between protein molecules\n- Disrupts protein structure and function\n- Potentially leads to protein aggregation\n\n6. Side Chain Oxidation\n- Modifies amino acid side chains\n- Can alter protein structure and reactivity\n- Affects protein stability and function\n\nThese modifications can significantly impact protein structure, function, and cellular processes.",
